In part (f), run all possible pairwise tests using Tukey’s Honestly Significan Difference procedure with the function TukeyHSD(). Apply TukeyHSD to the output you obtain by doing an analysis of variance with the aov() function (applied in the same manner as the lm() function). Use the defualt 95% (family-wise) confidence intervals. Summarize the conclusions of this procedure.

a. What are the correct hypotheses?

Null hypothesis(H0): \(\mu1\) = \(\mu2\) =\(\mu3\) = \(\mu4\), means are all the same
Alternative hypothesis(HA): At least one \(\mu i\) not equal to the others

b. Calculate the SSE and SSA by hand (without using lm, anova, or aov).

First way:

library(asbio)
## Loading required package: tcltk
data(life.exp)
X<-model.matrix(lifespan~treatment,data=life.exp)
Y<-life.exp$lifespan
beta.hat <- solve(t(X)%*% X)%*% t(X)%*% Y
I<-matrix(1,length(life.exp$lifespan),length(life.exp$lifespan))
SSA<-t(beta.hat)%*% t(X)%*% Y-(1/length(life.exp$lifespan))%*%t(Y)%*%I%*%Y
print(SSA)
##         [,1]
## [1,] 5267.03
SSE<-(t(Y)%*% Y - t(beta.hat)%*% t(X)%*% Y)
print(SSE)
##          [,1]
## [1,] 10802.94

e. Conduct and summarize the first 2 diagnostic procedures,and comment on the outcome.

plot(lm_life,which=1:2)

In residual vs Fitted plot, the plot allows you to see if the variability of the observations differs across the groups because all observations in the same group get the same fitted value

As the name suggests, this plot is used to determine the normal distribution of errors. It uses standardized values of residuals. Ideally, this plot should show a straight line. If you find a curved, distorted line, then your residuals have a non-normal distribution (problematic situation).

In our case, it also shows a quite linear line which suggests that it is a normal distribution.

f. Run all possible pairwise tests using Tukey’s Honestly Significan Difference procedure with the function TukeyHSD()

on the output you obtain by doing an analysis of variance with the aov() function applied in the same manner as the lm() functions. Use the defualt 95% (family.wise) confidence intervals. Summarize the conclusions of this procedure.

# methods specific to ANOVA
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
TukeyHSD(aov(lm_life)) # (note: we need to convert lm to aov here as TukeyHSD is specific to ANOVA)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = lm_life)
## 
## $treatment
##                   diff       lwr        upr     p adj
## N/R40-N/N85 12.4254385  9.215018 15.6358589 0.0000000
## N/R50-N/N85  9.6059554  6.519071 12.6928401 0.0000000
## R/R50-N/N85 10.1944862  6.928685 13.4602879 0.0000000
## N/R50-N/R40 -2.8194831 -5.863260  0.2242942 0.0804712
## R/R50-N/R40 -2.2309523 -5.456039  0.9941344 0.2808243
## R/R50-N/R50  0.5885309 -2.513604  3.6906659 0.9610849
plot(TukeyHSD(aov(lm_life), "treatment"))

The TukeyHSD compare the difference of mean for each group. In this case, we have four kinds of treatment. Therefore, it will generate 6 combinations for multiple testing. The p-value tells you if you can reject the null hypothesis. In other words, if the p-value is small enough, the means between groups are not equal. The plot clearly shows that comparison between groups with high p-value tend to have the 95% confidence interval around 0 (which is no difference).

The juul data frame in the “ISwR” library has 1339 rows and 6 columns. It contains a reference sample of the distribution of insulin-like growth factor (IGF-I), one observation per subject in various ages, with the bulk of the data collected in connection with school physical examinations.

a. Perform a one-way anova

Perform a one-way anova with the explanatory variable being the tanner variable, which is a 5-level factor giving an estimation of the stage of puberty based on the Tanner scale, and with a response variable of igf1 which is numeric and which measures insulin-like growth factor (micrograms/l). You may use the lm() and anova() functions.

library(ISwR)
data(juul)

b. Interpret the overall (omnibus) p-value.

The p-value is extremely small that we can reject the null hypothesis. In other words, at least one group of the mean difference of igf1 value for each group is not the same(not 0).

anova_juul<- anova(lm(igf1~tanner,data=juul))

Note: consider multiple testing correction.

Multiple testing correction refers to re-calculating probabilities obtained from a statistical test which was repeated multiple times. In order to retain a prescribed family-wise error rate α in an analysis involving more than one comparison, the error rate for each comparison must be more stringent than α. Boole’s inequality implies that if each of m tests is performed to have type I error rate α/m, the total error rate will not exceed α. This is called the Bonferroni correction, and is one of the most commonly used approaches for multiple comparisons.
